re, and integrate advanced technologies, including AI applications in biotechnology. \\nFaculty and Academic Experts:  Suggested to incorporate some examples of GMOs and guidelines of government policies and regulation for GENETIC. \\n• Suggested changes in syllabus of Biosensor subject  \\n  Food certificate and product certification should be separated. Include food packing regulations and techniques of food packaging \\nExperts recommended additions in ethical practices and tissue engineering methods. \\nIndustry Experts:  suggested Analog Electronics changes and in Digital subject, Biomaterials and Advanced computing for Biological Systems","feedbackAnalysis":"Feedback highlights need for curriculum modernization to ensure graduates possess up-to date competencies aligned with current industrial and  regulatory requirements. \\nAcademic experts emphasized content restructuring for conceptual clarity and industry relevance. \\nRedundancies identified (e.g., Kosher), and key international standards (Codex Alimentarius) need inclusion for global alignment. ","actionTakenReport":"Syllabus revision committee constituted; latest industrial trends reviewed and necessary updates incorporated into the curriculum. \\nCurriculum restructured:  \\n• Food certificate and product certification made separate modules.  \\n• Food packaging regulations and techniques added as a dedicated unit.  \\n• Kosher section removed due to limited academic relevance.  \\n• Codex standards incorporated under Food Safety module. \\n Existing Biosensors course expanded into “Biosensors and Devices” to enhance instrumentation and application skills. ","foreignCollaborations":"4\\n1. Dr. Ramendra Pati Pandey\\t\\nEvolutionary features of new picorna-like viruses in Culex (Melanoconion) mosquitoes\\t\\nLilian de Oliveira Guimaraes, Ariel Rocha de Almeida, Endrya do Socorro Foro Ramos, Juliana Telles-de-Deus, Vanessa Christe Helfstein, Vanessa dos Santos Morais, Jesus Maia dos Santos, Vera Lucia F